status_notes: Case Resolved. Gail,. As I stated over the phone with you,  Mayor Walsh and Boston Public Works Department realizes how important it is to maintain the street condition of Blue Hill Ave. Not only is it one of our most important streets, it is a major gateway in and out of the City. However we do not want to invest City money to pave a street if we know a utility or private contractor will be digging it in the near future. As you know, there is so much work going on in the City. That?s why in 2010 the Public Works Department created online reservation software called The City of Boston Coordination Software (COBUCS). Before receiving a permit, every utility company, private contractor, site plan engineer, City Departments, and Public Works paving projects all have to enter their work into the COBUCS system. The COBUCS system will alert the City and permittees of potential conflicts this will allow coordination to take place that wasn't done as successful before COBUCS. Since 2010 COBUCS has alerted the City of over 12,000 conflicts at a savings of over $40 million dollars of unnecessary paving fees if the street was cut after it was completed. No Street will be paved unless officially cleared through the COBUCS system. Boston is one of the few City's in the entire country that you cannot get a permit without entering the job into our online software. Unfortunately Blue Hill Ave has major conflicts. However, if the conflict is a new pipe or conduit which is a case on a lot of the Blue Hill Ave  proposed utility work then the City is getting what it should get from the utility,  full replacement of an old main or conduit. This not only gives the neighborhood superior utility services, but it also eliminates emergency repairs after we pave.  We are working with the utility companies to try to push their work up this year and next. Our goal is to try to pave Grove Hall this Fall or at the latest next Spring. Please reach out to my office and we can go over the proposed paving limits on Blue Hill Ave as well as the major utility conflicts. In the meantime I will have our CIU Inspectors drive all of Blue Hill Ave and make sure any substandard utility cut or casting is repaired to grade. . For any questions or concerns, please contact the number listed below. Sincerely,. Mark Cardarelli. Supervisor of Utility Coordination and Compliance. Boston Public Works Department. 617-635-4951 Office.
